title: McDonald lifts Natives
text:
Report Error 
Kyle McDonald scored two goals and set up another as his hometown Neepawa Natives edged the OCN Blizzard 5-4 in the Manitoba Junior Hockey League on Friday night. 
Elsewhere on Friday it was: Waywayseecappo Wolverines 5, Selkirk Steelers 3; Dauphin Kings 7, Winnipeg Blues 4; Portage Terriers 6, Swan Valley Stampeders 3; and Steinbach Pistons 3, Winkler Flyers 1. 
In The Pas, Reigan Buchanan of McCreary added a goal and an assist, while Jeremy Link stopped 38 shots for the Natives (5-6-0). Comacho Lathlin netted a pair of goals for OCN (3-5-2). 
Wolverines 5 Steelers 3 
At Selkirk, Brock Paddock of Rivers had a goal and two assists to pace Wayway (3-5-2), while Wayde Johnannesson added three helpers. Ty Kraus, Riley Derlago and Conner Barley replied for the Steelers (4-4-0). 
Kings 7 Blues 4 
At Dauphin, Matthew Greening and Romano Morrison each scored a goal and set up two others for the Kings (5-4-0), who struck four times in the middle frame. Kamerin Nault found the back of the net twice for Winnipeg (4-5-1). 
Terriers 6 Stampeders 3 
At Swan River, Brad Bowles had a goal and two helpers, while fellow Elkhorn native Brett Orr also scored for the league-leading Terriers (9-1-0), who took control with four goals in the middle period. Jordie Valentino, Evan Last and Colton Brausen had a goal and an assist each for the Stamps (2-7-1). 
Pistons 3 Flyers 1 
At Steinbach, Matthieu Gomercic scored twice for the Pistons (6-3-0), while Quintin Lisoway of Neepawa added another in his first game since being released by the WHL’s Brandon Wheat Kings. Brandonite Coltyn Bates replied for the Flyers (7-2-1). 
» The Brandon Sun
